discussing them, and lastly of seeking insight into how they are constituted in
their bodies. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Here
ends the part showing, by a discussion of four classes of individuals and three
kinds of individuals as given in the Sutta and Abhidhamma Pi</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>t</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>aka, that 1) those persons, who within
the Buddha S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
do not practise samatha and vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> but
allow the time to pass with imitations, suffer great loss as they fail to utilize
