<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>'Firmly established' means, if one
desires to place the attention on out-breath and in-breath for an hour, one¡¦s
attention remains firmly fixed on it for that period. If one wishes to do so
for two hours, one¡¦s attention remains firmly fixed on it for two hours. There
is no occasion when the attention becomes released from its object on account
of the instability of thought-conception (vitakkha). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>(For a detailed account of the satipa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na,
see the Mah</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>satipa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na Sutta.<a style='mso-footnote-id:ftn43'
href="#_ftn43" name="_ftnref43" title=""><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow;mso-shading:yellow'><span
style='mso-special-character:footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]>[43]<![endif]></span></span></span></a>)
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Why is it incumbent on us to firmly
establish the mind without fail on any object such as the out-breath and the
in-breath? It is because it is necessary for us to gather and control the six
vi</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bban</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a,<a style='mso-footnote-id:
ftn44' href="#_ftn44" name="_ftnref44" title=""><span
class=MsoFootnoteReference><span style='background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow;
mso-shading:yellow'><span style='mso-special-character:footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]>[44]<![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
style='background:yellow'> </span>which have been drifting tempestuously and
untrained throughout the past inconceivably long and beginningless sa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra
(round of rebirths). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>I shall make it clear. The mind is wont
to flit about from one to another of the six objects of the senses which live
at the approaches of the six sense-doors.<a style='mso-footnote-id:ftn45'
href="#_ftn45" name="_ftnref45" title=""><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]>[45]<![endif]></span></span></span></a> <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>As an example, take the case of a mad man
who has no control over his mind. He does not even know the meal-time, and
wanders about aimlessly from place to place. His parents look for him and give
him his meal. After eating five or six morsels of food, he overturns the dish
and walks away. He thus fails to get a square meal. To this extent he has lost
control of his mind. He cannot control his mind even to the extent of finishing
the business of a meal. In talking, he cannot control his mind to the extent of
finishing or completing a sentence. The beginning, the middle, and the end do
not agree with one another. His talk has no meaning. He cannot be of use in any
undertaking in this world. He is unable to perform any task. Such a person can
no longer be classed as a human being, and he has to be ignored. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>This mad man becomes a sane and normal
person again if he meets a good doctor and the doctor applies such stringent
methods of cure as tying him up and putting him in chains. Thus cured, he
obtains control of his mind in the matter of taking his meals, and can now eat
his fill. He has control over his mind in all other matters as well. He can
perform his tasks till they are completed, just like others. Just like others,
he can also complete his sentences. This is the example. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In this world, persons who are not
insane, but who are normal and have control over their minds, resemble such a
mad person having no control over his mind when it comes to the matter of
samatha and vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>. Just as the man upsets the
food dish and walks away after five or six morsels of food athough he attempts
to eat his meal, these normally sane persons find their attention wandering
because they have no control over their minds. Whenever they pay respects to
the Buddha and contemplate his noble qualities, they do not succeed in keeping
their minds fixed on those noble qualities, but find their attention being
diverted many times on to other objects of thought, and thus they fail to reach
the end of even the 'itipiso' verse.<a style='mso-footnote-id:ftn46'
href="#_ftn46" name="_ftnref46" title=""><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]>[46]<![endif]></span></span></span></a> <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>It is as if a man suffering from
hydrophobia who seeks water feverishly with parched lips, yet runs away from it
with fear when he sees a lake of cool refreshing water. It is also like a
diseased man who when given a diet of relishing food replete with medicinal
qualities, finds the food bitter to his taste and unable to swallow it and is
obliged to spit and vomit it out. In just the same way, these persons find
themselves unable to approach the contemplation of the noble qualities of the
Buddha effectively and cannot keep on dwelling on them. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>If in reciting the 'itipiso' verse, their
recitation is interrupted every time their minds wander, and if they have to
start afresh from the beginning every time such an interruption occurs, they
will never reach the end of the verse even though they keep on reciting a whole
day, or a whole month, or a whole year. At present they manage to reach the end
because they can keep on reciting from memory even though their minds wander
elsewhere. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In the same way, those persons who, on
uposatha days, plan to go to quiet places in order to contemplate the
thirty-two parts of the body, such as kesa (hairs of the head), loma (hairs of
the body), etc., or the noble qualities of the Buddha, ultimately end up in the
company of friends and associates because they have no control over their
minds, and because of the upheavals in their thoughts and intentions. When they
take part in congregational recitations,<a style='mso-footnote-id:ftn47'
href="#_ftn47" name="_ftnref47" title=""><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow;mso-shading:yellow'><span
style='mso-special-character:footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]>[47]<![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
style='background:yellow'> </span>although they attempt to direct their minds
to the samatha (calm) work of the brahma-vihara (sublime states),<a
style='mso-footnote-id:ftn48' href="#_ftn48" name="_ftnref48" title=""><span
class=MsoFootnoteReference><span style='background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow;
mso-shading:yellow'><span style='mso-special-character:footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]>[48]<![endif]></span></span></span></a>
such as reciting the formula for diffusing metta (loving-kindness), because
they have no control over their minds, their thoughts are not concentrated but
are scattered aimlessly, and they end up only with the visible manifestation of
the recitation. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>These facts are sufficient to show how
many persons resemble the insane while performing kusala kamma (merit). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Papasmim ramate mano. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The mind takes delight in evil.<a
style='mso-footnote-id:ftn49' href="#_ftn49" name="_ftnref49" title=""><span
class=MsoFootnoteReference><span style='background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow;
mso-shading:yellow'><span style='mso-special-character:footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]>[49]<![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
style='background:yellow'> </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Just as water naturally flows down from
high places to low places, the minds of beings, if left uncontrolled, naturally
approach evils. This is the tendency of the mind. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>I shall now draw, with examples, a
comparison between those who exercise no control over their minds and the
insane person mentioned above. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>There is a river with a swift current. A
boatman not conversant with the control of the rudder, floats down the river
with the current. His boat is loaded with valuable merchandise for trading and
selling at the towns on the lower reaches of the river. As he floats down, he
passes stretches of the river lined with mountains and forests where there are
no harbours or anchorages for his boat. He thus continues to float down without
stopping. When night descends, he passes towns and villages with harbours and
anchorages, but he does not see them in the darkness of the night, and thus he
continues to float down without stopping. When daylight arrives, he comes to
places with towns and villages, but not having any control over the rudder of
the boat, he cannot steer it to the harbours and anchorages, and thus perforce
he continues to float down until he reaches the great wide ocean. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The infinitely lengthy sa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra
(round of rebirths) is like the swift flowing river. Beings having no control
over their minds are like the boatman who is unable to steer his boat. The mind
is like the boat. Beings who have drifted from one existence to another in the ¡¥su</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bb</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a¡¦ world-cycles, where no Buddha S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s
appear, are like the boatman drifting down those stretches of the river lined
by mountains and forests, where there are no harbous and anchorages. When at
times these beings are born in world-cycles where Buddha S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s
flourish, but are in ignorance of them because they happen to be in one or
other of the eight atthakkhana (inopportune places), they resemble the boatman
who floats down stretches of the river lined by towns and villages with
harbours and anchorages, but does not see them because it is night. When at
other times, they are born as human beings, devas or Brahmas, within a Buddha S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
but fail to secure the Paths and the Fruits because they are unable to control
their minds and put forth effort to practise vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
(insight) exercises of the satipa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na (the four applications of mindfulness)
thus continuing still to drift in sa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra, they resemble the boatman who sees
the banks lined by towns and villages with harbours and anchorages, but is
unable to steer towards them because of his inability to control the rudder,
and thus continues perforce to drift down towards the ocean. In the infinite sa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra,
those beings who have obtained release from worldly ills within the S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s
of the Buddhas who have appeared, whose numbers exceed the grains of sand on
the banks of the river Ganges, are beings who had control over their minds and
who possessed the ability of retaining their attention on any desired object at
will through the practice of the satipa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>This shows the trend of the wandering or
'course of existence' of those beings who do not practise the satipa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na,
even though they are aware of the fact that they have no control over their
minds when it comes to the practice of samatha and vipassan</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> (calm and insight). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Comparisons may also be made with the
taming and training of bullocks for the purpose of yoking to ploughs and carts,
and to the taming and training of elephants for employment in the service of
the king, or on battlefields. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In the case of the bullock, the young
calf has to be regularly herded and kept in a cattle-pen, then a nose-rope is
passed through its nostrils and it is tied to a post and trained to respond to
the rope¡¦s control. It is then trained to submit to the yoke, and only when it
becomes amenable to the yoke¡¦s burden is it put to use for ploughing and
drawing carts and thus effectively employed for trade and profit. This is the
example of the bullock. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In this example, just as the owner¡¦s
profit and success depends on the employment of the bullock in the drawing of
ploughs and carts after training it to become amenable to the yoke, so do the
true benefits of lay persons and bhikkhus within the present S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
depend on training in samatha and vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
(calm and insight). In the present Buddha S</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, the practice of s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la-visuddhi (purification of virtue)
resembles the training of the young calf by herding it and keeping it in
cattle-pens. Just as if the young calf is not so herded and kept in cattle-pens
it would damage and destroy the properties of others and thus bring liability
on the owner, so if a person lacks s</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la-visuddhi,
the three kamma<a style='mso-footnote-id:ftn50' href="#_ftn50" name="_ftnref50"
title=""><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span style='background:yellow;
mso-highlight:yellow;mso-shading:yellow'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]>[50]<![endif]></span></span></span></a>
would run riot, and the person concerned would become subject to worldly evils
and to the evil results indicated in the dhamma. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The effort to develop k</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-satipa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na<a style='mso-footnote-id:ftn51'
href="#_ftn51" name="_ftnref51" title=""><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow;mso-shading:yellow'><span
style='mso-special-character:footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]>[51]<![endif]></span></span></span></a><span
style='background:yellow'> </span><span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">&nbsp;</span>resembles the passing of the nose-rope through the nostrils
and training the calf to respond to the rope after tying it to a post. Just as
when a calf is tied to a post it can be kept wherever the owner desires it to
be, and it cannot run loose, so when the mind is tied to the body with the rope
called satipa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na,
that mind cannot wander but is obliged to remain wherever the owner desires it
to be. The habits of a disturbed and distracted mind acquired during the
inconceivably long sa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra
become appeased. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>A person who performs the practice of
samatha and vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> (calm and insight) without
first attempting k</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-satipa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na
(mindfulness as regards the body), resembles the owner who yokes the still
untamed bullock to the cart or plough without the nose-rope. Such an owner
would find himself unable to drive the bullock at his desire. Because the
bullock is wild, and because it has no nose-rope, it will either try to run off
the road, or try to break loose by breaking the yoke. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>On the other hand, a person who first
tranquillises and trains his mind with k</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-satipa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na
-bh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
(contemplation of the body) before turning his mind to the practice of samatha
and vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> (calm and insight), his
attention will remain steady and his work will be successful. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In the case of the elephant, the wild
elephant has first to be brought out from the forest into the field hitched to
a tame trained elephant. Hence it is taken to a stockade and tied up securely
until it is tame. When it thus becomes absolutely tame and quiet, it is trained
in the various kinds of work in which it will be employed in the service of the
king. It is only then that it is used in state functions and on battlefields. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The realm of sensual pleasures resembles
the forest where the wild elephant enjoys himself. The Buddha S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
resembles the open field into which the wild elephant is first brought out. The
mind resembles the wild elephant. Faith (saddha) and desire (chanda) in the S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-dhamma
resemble the tame elephant to which the wild elephant is hitched and brought
out into the open. S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la-visuddhi (purification of
virtue) resembles the stockade. The body, or parts of the body, such as
out-breath and in-breath resemble the post in the stockade to which the
elephant is tied.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp; </span>K</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagati-sati resembles the rope by which
the wild elephant is tied to the post. The preparatory work towards samatha and
vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> resembles the preparatory
training of the elephant. The work of and samatha and vipassan</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> resembles the parade ground or
battlefield of the king. Other points of comparison can now be easily recognised.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Thus have I shown by the examples of the
mad man, the boatman, the bullock, and the elephant, the main points of k</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati, which is by ancient
tradition the first step that has to be undertaken in the work of proceeding
upwards from s</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la-visuddhi within the S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
\s of all the Buddhas who have appeared in the past inconceivably long sa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The essential meaning is, whether it be
by out-breathing or in-breathing, or by iriyapatha (four postures--going,
standing, sitting, lying) or by sampajanna, (clear-comprehension), or by dhatu-
manasik</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra (advertence of mind on the
elements), or by atthika-sanna (contemplation of bones), one must put forth
effort in order to acquire the ability of placing one¡¦s attention on one¡¦s body
and its postures for as long as one wishes throughout the day and night at all
waking hours. If one can keep one¡¦s attention fixed for as long as one wishes,
then mastery has been obtained over one¡¦s mind. Thus does one attain release
from the state of a mad man. One now resembles the boatman who has obtained
mastery over his rudder, or the owner of the tamed and trained bullock, or the
king who employs the tamed and trained elephant. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>There are many kinds and many grades of
mastery over the mind. The successful practice of k</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati
is, in the Buddha S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
the first stage of mastery over one¡¦s mind. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Those who do not wish to follow the way
of samatha (calm), but desire to pursue the path of pure vipassan</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, which is the way of the
sukkha-vipassaka<a style='mso-footnote-id:ftn52' href="#_ftn52" name="_ftnref52"
title=""><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span style='background:yellow;
mso-highlight:yellow'><span style='mso-special-character:footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]>[52]<![endif]></span></span></span></a>
individual, should proceed straight to vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
after the successful establishment of k</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati.
If they do not want to practise k</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati
separately and if they mean to practise vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
with such industry that it may carry k</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati
with it, they will succeed, provided that they really have the necessary wisdom
and industry. The k</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati that is associated
with udayabbaya-</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>ban</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a (knowledge arising from
contemplation of the arisings and vanishings of mental and physical phenomena),
which clearly sees their coming into existence and passing away, is very
valuable indeed. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In the samatha (calm) method, by
practising the k</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati of out-breathing
and in-breathing, one can attain up to r</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>u</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>pavac</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra-catuttha-jh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na
(the fourth Jh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na of the form-sphere); by practising
vanna-mana-sikara<a style='mso-footnote-id:ftn53' href="#_ftn53"
name="_ftnref53" title=""><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]>[53]<![endif]></span></span></span></a> of
the k</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati of the thirty-two
parts of the body, such as kesa (hair of the head), loma (hair of the body),
etc., one can attain all the eight samapatti<a style='mso-footnote-id:ftn54'
href="#_ftn54" name="_ftnref54" title=""><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]>[54]<![endif]></span></span></span></a> and
by practising<a style='mso-footnote-id:ftn55' href="#_ftn55" name="_ftnref55"
title=""><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span style='background:yellow;
mso-highlight:yellow'><span style='mso-special-character:footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]>[55]<![endif]></span></span></span></a>
patikula-manasik</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra of the same k</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati one can attain the first jh</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na. If vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
(insight) is attained in the process, one also can attain the Paths and the
Fruits. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Even if completion is not arrived at in
the practice of samatha and vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> (calm
and insight), if the stage is reached where one attains control over one¡¦s mind
and the ability to keep one¡¦s attention fixed on wherever one wishes it to be,
it was said by the Buddha that such a one can be said to be one who enjoys the
savour of amata nibb</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na.<a style='mso-footnote-id:
ftn56' href="#_ftn56" name="_ftnref56" title=""><span
class=MsoFootnoteReference><span style='background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow'><span
style='mso-special-character:footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]>[56]<![endif]></span></span></span></a><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<pre style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>¡¥Amatam paribhuttam,<a
style='mso-footnote-id:ftn57' href="#_ftn57" name="_ftnref57" title=""><span
class=MsoFootnoteReference><span style='background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow'><span
style='mso-special-character:footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]>[57]<![endif]></span></span></span></a><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>These who enjoy k</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati,<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre
style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Yesam k</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata sati paribhutta.¡¦<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>enjoy amata (</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-bidi-font-family:"Courier New"'>nibb</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-bidi-font-family:"Courier New"'>na</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>).<o:p></o:p></span></pre>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Here, amata (nibb</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na) means great peacefulness or
tranquillity of mind.<a style='mso-footnote-id:ftn58' href="#_ftn58"
name="_ftnref58" title=""><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow'><span style='mso-special-character:
footnote'><![if !supportFootnotes]>[58]<![endif]></span></span></span></a><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In its original natal state, the mind is
highly unstable in its attentiveness, and thus is parched and hot in its
nature. Just as the insects that live on capsicum are not aware of its heat,
just as beings pursuing the realm of ta</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> (craving) are not aware of ta</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
¡¦s heat, just as beings subject to anger and pride are not aware of the heat of
pride and anger, so are beings unaware of the heat of unsettled minds. It is
only when, through k</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati, the unsettlement
of their minds disappear, do they become aware of the heat of unsettled minds.
Having attained the state of the disappearance of that, they develop a fear of
a relapse to that heat. The case of those who have attained the first jh</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na, or udayabbaya-</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>ban</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a, through k</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-satipa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na
needs no elaboration. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Hence, the higher the attainments that
one reaches, the more does it become difficult for one to be apart from k</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati The ariya puggala (holy ones)
use the four satipa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na
as mental nutriment until they attain Parinibb</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The ability to keep one¡¦s attention fixed
on parts of the body, such as out-breath and in-breath, for one or two hours
takes one to the culmination of one¡¦s work in seven days, or fifteen days, or a
month, or two months, or three months, or four months, or five months, or six
months, or a year, or two years, or three years, according to the intensity of
one¡¦s efforts. For the method of practising out-breathing and in-breathing, see
my </span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>A</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>pana
D</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>pan</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>There are many books by past teachers on
the method of the thirtytwo parts of the body. In this method, kesa (hair of
the head), loma (hair of the body), nakha (nails), danta (teeth), taco (skin)
are known as taca-pancaka (group ending with taco as the fifth). If attention
can be firmly fixed on these five, the work of k</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati
is accomplished. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>For catu-dhatu-vavatthana (analysis of
the four great primaries), r</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>u</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>pa- vipassan</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> (contemplation of physical phenomena),
and n</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ma-vipassan</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> (contemplation of mental phenomena), see
my Lakkha</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a D</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>pan</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, Vijj</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
-Magga D</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>pan</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
Ah</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra D</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>pan</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, and Anatta D</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>pan</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Here ends a concise explanation of k</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagtasati-bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, which is one of the four satipa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na,
and which has to be established first in the work of bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> (mental contemplation) by neyya and
padaparama individuals for the purpose of attaining the Paths and the Fruits
within a Buddha S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Here ends satipa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

