      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>let the bones remain <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l2 level2 lfo6;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>let the flesh and blood dry up. <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 </ol>
</ul>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>It is effort that calls forth the
determination 'If the end is attainable by human effort, I shall not rest or
relax until it is attained, until the end is grasped and reached.' It is the
effort of the kind put forth by the Venerable Bhikkhu Sona[60] and the
Venerable Cakkhupala.[61] <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>It is only when the jh</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na, the Paths, and the Fruits are not
attained after effort is put forth on this scale, as prescribed by the Buddha,
throughout one¡¦s life, can it be said that the cause (of the failure) lies in
the nature of the present times, or in one being dvi-hetuka (born with two root
conditions only), or in one¡¦s lack of sufficient previously accumulated p</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ram</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In this world, some persons, far from
putting forth the full scale of the effort prescribed by the Buddha, do not
even try to set up k</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati effectively in
order to cure their minds of aimless drifting, and yet they say that their
failure to attain the Paths and the Fruits is due to the fact that these are
times that preclude such attainment. There are others of the same class who say
that men and women of the present day have not the necessary accumulation of p</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ram</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
to enable them to attain the Paths and the Fruits. There are yet others of the
same class who say that men and women of the present day are dvi-hetuka. All these
people say so because they do not know that these are times of the neyya class
of individuals who fail to attain the Paths and the Fruits because they are
lacking in sammappadh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
effort. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>If proper sammappadh</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
effort be put forth with pahitatta intention, where a thousand put forth
effort, three, four or five hundred of them can attain the supreme achievement;
if a hundred put forth effort, thirty, forty, or fifty of them can attain the
supreme achievement. Here, pahitatta intention means 'determination to adhere
to the effort throughout one¡¦s life and to die, if need be, while still making
the effort.' <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The Venerable Sona Thera¡¦s effort
consisted of keeping awake throughout the three months of the vassa (rainy
season), the only body postures adopted being sitting and walking. The
Venerable Cakkhupala¡¦s effort was of the same order. The Venerable Phussadeva
Thera[62] achieved the Paths and the Fruits only after twenty-five years of the
same order of effort. In the case of the Venerable Mah</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>siva[63]
Thera, the effort lasted thirty years. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>At the present day, there is a great need
for such kind of sammappadh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
effort. It happens that those who put forth the effort have not sufficient
foundations in the pariyatti (learning of the doctrine), while those who
possess sufficient pariyatti foundations live involved in the palibodha
(obstacles) of the business of bhikkhus, according as they live in towns and
villages, such as discussing the Dhamma, delivering sermons and discourses, and
writing books on the Dhamma. They are persons who are unable to put forth
sammappadh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
effort for lengthy periods without a break. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Some persons are wont to say that when
their p</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ram</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
become mature and the time becomes ripe for them to attain release from worldly
ills they can easily obtain that release and that as such, they cannot put
forth effort now when they are not certain whether of not that effort will
result in release. They do not appear to compare the suffering occasioned by
thirty years' effort now with the suffering they will encounter if, in the
interim before they attain release, they are cast in the hell regions for a
hundred thousand years. They do not appear to remember that the suffering
occasioned by thirty years' effort is not as bad as the suffering caused by
just three hours in the hell regions. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>They may say that the situation will be
the same if no release is attained after thirty years' effort. But if the
person is sufficiently mature for release, he will attain that release through
that effort. If he is not sufficiently mature, he will attain release in the
next life. Even if he fails to attain release within the present Buddha S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
bh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-aci</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>nn</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a-kamma (the kamma of repeated efforts at
mental development) is a powerful kamma. Through it he can avoid the apaya
regions and can meet the next Buddha after continuous rebirths in the sugati
existence (happy course of existence). In the case of those who do not put
forth the effort, they will miss the opportunity of release even though they
are mature enough to obtain release through thirty years' effort. For lack of
effort they have nothing to gain and everything to lose. Let all, therefore,
acquire the eye of wisdom, and beware of the danger. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

