style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The coarse di</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi
of vitikkama comprises the akusala kamma committed through overt acts and
speech. The middling di</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi of pariyutthana comprises
the evils that occur in thoughts. Anusaya- di</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi
is the evil that lies latent in the personalities of beings throughout
anamatagga-sa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra
though it may not yet result in manifestations of acts, speech, or thoughts. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>It may be said that there are three kinds
of fire in a match-box. The first is the fire that lies latent in the whole box
of matches. The second is the fire that ignites the match stick when it is
struck. The third is the fire that is transferred to another object when it is
brought in contact with the flame of the match stick. Such a fire is that which
burns rubbish heaps, clothes, houses, monasteries and villages. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>This fire, the fire that is transferred
to another object, resembles the coarse vitakkama-di</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi.
The fire that burns the match stick resembles the middling pariyutthana di</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi which is manifested in the mind every
time it comes in contact with objects of thought. The fire that is latent in
the box of matches resembles the fine anusaya-di</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi
that resides in the personalities of beings throughout the succession of lives
in anama-tagga-sa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>This fire that lies latent in the box of
matches does not burst into flame so long as the match head is not rubbed with
the nitrous surface of the match-box, It does not cause any harm even if it be
kept in contact with highly inflammable articles such as gunpowder. In the same
way, the anusaya-di</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi lies latent in the
personality and does not manifest itself so long as it does not come into
contact with evil objects of thought or other causes of evil. When, however,
evil objects of thought or other causes impinge on the six sense-doors, the
anusaya-di</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi is disturbed and begins to
make itself manifest in the mind-door, or in the plane of the pariyutthana
through the function of volition. If at that time the manifestations can be
suppressed by good doctrines, they disappear from the pariyutthana plane and
return to the anusaya plane and reside there as latent natural tendencies. If
they cannot be suppressed, they continue to manifest themselves as developing
volitions. If they are further disturbed (in the pariyutthana plane), they
manifest themselves in the vitikkama plane in the form of evil speech or evil
acts. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In this world, if a person can control
himself in the vitikkama and pariyutthana planes, and if thereby his acts,
speech, and thoughts are, so to say, clean and unsoiled, he is called a good,
pious, or moral man. But such a person is not aware of the anusaya plane. If
the anusaya plane is not destroyed, even if perfect control is exercised over
the vitikkama and pariyutthana planes, such control can only be of a temporary
nature. If the person is strong in the observance of good principles, the
control can last for the whole of this life. But there can be no certainty
about the next life, when upheavals in these two planes may recur. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Lobha (greed), dosa (hatred), and moha
(delusion) also have each of them three planes. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In order to destroy these three planes of
di</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi completely, men have to put
forth effort in the three sikkha (trainings) of s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la
(morality), sam</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi (concentration), and pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> (wisdom). They have to practise the
seven visuddhi (purifications). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>As far as layfolk are concerned, s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
