<h3 style='tab-stops:24.0pt'><a name="_Toc133723543"></a><a name="_Toc133724047"><span
style='mso-bookmark:_Toc133723543'><span lang=EN-US>IV, The Four Iddhipadda</span></span></a></h3>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>I shall now give a brief
description of iddhipdda. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Ijjhana</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
iddhi, (ijjhana</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>: completeness; iddhi:
completeness) (The state of reaching completeness or perfection). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>(Note:--The PTS Dictionary says: 'There
is no single word for iddhi as the idea is unknown in Europe. The main sense
seems to be potency.' --Translator.) <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In the Buddha S</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> there are five iddhi. They are: <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<ul type=disc>
 <ol start=1 type=1>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l7 level2 lfo8;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Abhinneyyesu dhammesu abhinnasiddhi
      <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l7 level2 lfo8;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Parinneyyesu dhammesu parinnasiddhi
      <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l7 level2 lfo8;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Pahatabbesu dhammesu pahanasiddhi <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l7 level2 lfo8;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Sacchikatabbesu dhammesu
      sacchikiriyasiddhi <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l7 level2 lfo8;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Bhavetabbesu dhammesu bh</span><span
      lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
      "Times New Roman"'>siddhi. <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l7 level2 lfo8;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Completion of or perfection in
      acquiring special knowledge in those things in which special knowledge
      should be acquired, things such as r</span><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:Foreign1'>u</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
      "Times New Roman"'>pa (material phenomena), n</span><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
      "Times New Roman"'>ma (mental phenomena); <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l7 level2 lfo8;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Completion of or perfection in
      acquiring full understanding in those things in which full understanding
      should be acquired, things such as dukkha-sacca (the Noble Truth of
      Suffering); <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l7 level2 lfo8;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Completion of or perfection
      attained in the task of abandonment of those things that should be
      abandoned, things such as samudaya-sacca (the Noble Truth of the Cause of
      Suffering); <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l7 level2 lfo8;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Completion of or perfection
      attained in the task of realization of those things that should be
      realized, things such as nirodha-sacca (the Noble Truth of the Cessation
      of Suffering); <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l7 level2 lfo8;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Completion of or perfection
      attained in the task of development or cultivation of those things that
      should be developed or cultivated, things such as magga-sacca (the Noble
      Truth of the Path Leading to the Cessation of Suffering). <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 </ol>
</ul>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>These are the five essential iddhi within
a Buddha S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Abhinnasiddhi means:</span></b><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> the completion of the task of
knowing analytically the number and meaning of the paramattha dhamma (ultimate
truths) which one had no knowledge of while one was beyond the pale of a Buddha
S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.
A thorough knowledge of the Abhidhammattha Sa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>gaha
(a resume of all the essential doctrines of the Abhidhamma) amounts to
abhinnasiddhi. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Parinnasiddhi means:</span></b><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> the completion of acquiring
full understanding of dukkha sacca, (the Noble Truth of Suffering) either
through a knowledge of their lakkhana (characteristics), rasa (functions),
paccupatthana (manifestations), and padatthana (proximate causes), or through a
knowledge of the three characteristics of anicca (impermanence), dukkha
(suffering), and anatta (impersonality), which they possess. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Pahanasiddhi means:</span></b><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> the completion of the task of
destroying the kilesa (defilements) which are samudaya sacca (the Noble Truth
of the Cause of Suffering). In this book, since the main emphasis is placed on
the attainment of the lowest class of sotapannas, namely the 'bon-sin-san'
sotapannas, and not on the higher classes of ariyas (noble ones), the completion
of the task of destroying sakk</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ya-di</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi
(personality-belief) is pahanasiddhi. The task of dispelling vicikiccha
(sceptical doubt) is comprised within the taks of destroying sakk</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ya-di</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Sacchikiriyasiddhi means: the completion
of the task of realizing nirodha sacca (the Noble Truth of the Cessation of
Suffering) both bodily and mentally. This task consists of the suppression and
destruction of the kilesa (defilements). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>siddhi means: the development of the
three sikkha (trainings) of s</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la (morality), sam</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi (mental concentration) and pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> (wisdom), until the attainment of
lokuttara-magga-sacca. (supramundane Path leading to the cessation of
suffering). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>If the iddhi be classified according to
the order of the visuddhi, the fulfilment of catuparisuddhi-s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la in s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la-visuddhi
constitutes four iddhi. In citta-visuddhi, the fulfilment of the eight
samapatti together with parikamma- sam</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi
(preparatory concentration) and upac</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra-sam</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi (neighbourhood concentration), as the
case may be, constitutes eight iddhi. The fulfilment of the five lokiya abhinna
(mundane higher spiritual powers), such as iddhividha-abhinna (supernormal
powers), constitutes five iddhi. In the pa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
"Times New Roman"'>-visuddhi the fulfilment of di</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi-visuddhi
constitutes one iddhi. In this way, further iddhi may also be recognised. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Here ends the discussion of iddhi within
the S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<h4><a name="_Toc133723544"></a><a name="_Toc133724048"><span style='mso-bookmark:
_Toc133723544'><span lang=EN-US>Iddhipada</span></span></a></h4>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Iddhiya pado iddhipado
(iddhiya: of attaining completion or perfection; pado: root or basis. The root
or basis of attaining completion or perfection. Hence it is called iddhipada). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>There are four kinds of iddhipada. They
are: <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<ul type=disc>
 <ol start=11 type=1>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l7 level2 lfo8;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>chandiddhipado-chanda <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l7 level2 lfo8;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>viryaddhipado-v</span><span
      lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l7 level2 lfo8;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>cittiddhipado-citta <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l7 level2 lfo8;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>vimamsiddhipado-vimamsa or pa</span><span
      lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>. <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 </ol>
</ul>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>By chanda is meant desire to obtain,
desire to attain, desire to reach, desire to fulfil, desire to accomplish, The
desire indicated here is extreme or excessive desire. There is nothing within
or without one¡¦s personality that can obstruct that desire. It is the kind of
desire that evokes the thought, 'If I do not attain this accomplishment in this
life, I shall not rest content. It is better that I die rather than that I
shall not attain it.' <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>It is the kind of desire nurtured by King
Dhammasonda of Banaras during the time of the Kassapa Buddha,[83] when the king
said to himself, 'What use is there in my being king of Banaras if I do not get
the opportunity of hearing a discourse of the Kassapa Buddha?'[84] The king,
therefore, relinquished his throne and went out in search of one who could
repeat to him a discourse of the Kassapa Buddha, no matter though that
discourse consisted of a short stanza only. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Such desire is appeased if it is
fulfilled as in the case of King Bimbisara,[85] Visakha, and Anathapindika. It
is only when there are faint indications that the desire can be attained but is
not fulfilled that the mind becomes troubled, and thoughts arise that it is
better to die than live without attaining the desire. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Examples of such desire existed also in
King Temiya,[86] King Hatthipala,[87] and kings, nobles, and rich men in the
time of the Buddha who discarded their palaces, retinue and other luxuries to
live the lives of bhikkhus in the Buddha S</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>V</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya
means sammappadh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
viriya together with its four characteristics. A person with this viriya is
infused with the thought that the aim can be attained by energy and effort. He
is not discouraged even though it is said to him that he must undergo great
hardships. He is not discouraged even though he actually has to undergo great
hardships. He is not discouraged even though it is said to him that he must put
forth effort for many days, months, and years. He is not discouraged even
though he actually has to put forth effort for such long periods. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Those who are weak in v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya recoil from their task when
confronted with work requiring great energy and effort. They shrink when told
that they will have to stay apart from friends and associates. They shrink from
the prospect of the necessity to be frugal in sleep and food. They shrink from
the prospect of long periods of concentration. They resemble 'white dogs that
dare not venture into thickets.' White dogs are afraid to enter brushes of
reeds that are no more than a cubit high because they think that the brushes
might harbour leopards, tigers, and elephants. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Citta means: attachment to iddhi when one
comes in contact with the S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
and hears the Dhamma. It is attachment that is extremely ardent and strong. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Although one lives amidst the beauties
and luxuries of the world, amidst acquired powers and fortunes, amidst the
sacred books and the study of them, one is not allured, but one¡¦s mind is
always turned towards the iddhi. One attains satisfaction and tranquillity only
when one¡¦s mind is absorbed in matters connected with the iddhi. It is like the
absorption of the alchemist engaged in the transmutation of the baser metals
into gold or silver. Such an alchemist has no interest in anything else but his
alchemy. He forgets to sleep or whether he had slept or eaten. He does not
notice anything when out walking. Citta is great absorption or attachment of
this nature. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Vimamsa means: knowledge or wisdom that
can clearly perceive the greatness of the sufferings of hell, and of the
sufferings attendant on the round of rebirths. It is knowledge that can clearly
perceive the advantages and benefits of the iddhi. It is knowledge that can
dwell on the deep and difficult dhamma, and on their nature. A person who
possesses such knowledge can no longer find pleasure in any worldly pursuit except
the pursuit of the iddhi. He finds gratification only in the acquisition of
deep and profound iddhi. The deeper and more profound the dhamma, the greater
is his desire to attain them. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Those who are endowed with any one of
these four iddhipada can no longer, during this life, admit or plead inability
and remain without putting forth effort in the establishinentof k</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati, and the higher stages of the
S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
such as citta-visuddhi, di</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi-visuddhi, etc. It is only
those who have never possessed any one of these iddhipada, and who cannot
differentiate between the shallowness and profoundness of life, between
superficiality and deepness of the dhamma, who adinit or plead inability and
remain without making any endeavour. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>A person endowed with any one of these
four iddhipada can attain, according to his p</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ram</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, the iddhi until he reaches lokuttara
(supramundane) iddhi, either in this life or as a deva in the next life. The
cases of those endowed with two, or three, or four, iddhi need no lengthy explanation.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In the cases of those persons who (far
from possessing any of the iddhi) do not even possess any of the iddhipada,
they should attempt to acquire one or other of these pada. They admit or plead
inability only because they have not the desire to acquire the higher benefits
of the S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
such as the satipaitthana. They should regard this very admission of inability
as a highway to the apayaloka. Thus, they should study, think and ponder, over
the suttanta discourses that can arouse chanda. They should approach a teacher
who can arouse chanda and rely on him. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Hence did the Buddha say: <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<pre style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Chandiddhipada</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>veti,<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre
style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Viriyiddhipada</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>veti,<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre
style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Cittiddhipada</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>veti,<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre
style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Vimamsiddhipada</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>veti.[87]<o:p></o:p></span></pre>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>(One should put forth effort
to develop chanda; one should put forth effort to develop v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya; one should put forth effort to
develop citta; and one should put forth effort to develop v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ma</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>sa.)
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Some persons, far from attaining the
iddhi, do not even try to attain the iddhipada. If they do not possess chanda,
they do not even know that it is necessary to acquire chanda. They are persons
who admit and plead inability and defeat. The same is true in the cases of v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya, citta, and v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ma</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>sa.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Steady application of the mind to k</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati amounts to setting up pada.
Studying the anecdotes dealing with sa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>vega,[88]
applying oneself to dhuta</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga[89] and such other
practices of the dhamma, is setting up v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya.
Applying oneself to profound dhamma, such as the four great primaries[90]
amounts to setting up vimamsa. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>If any one of the pada is established,
then it is certain that the respective iddhi will be attained according to one¡¦s
p</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ram</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.
Hence, it is stated in the commentaries that persons who do not possess any one
of the iddhipada resemble the sons of a candala,[91] while persons possessing
any one of the pada resemble the sons of an emperor. The sons of candala never
aim at becoming an emperor because they have no basis, no pada, for the
attainment of such an aim. Sons of emperors, however, always aim at becoming
emperors because they are endowed with the bases for the attainment of such an
aim. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Hence, wise persons of the present day
should attempt to acquire the four iddhipada so that they can destroy the great
establishment of sakk</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yadi-tthi
(personality-belief), and to attain, within the S</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, the benefits of the higher attainments
that can be attained according to one¡¦s p</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ram</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

