<h4><a name="_Toc133723549"></a><a name="_Toc133724050"><span style='mso-bookmark:
_Toc133723549'><span lang=EN-US>Indriya means:</span></span></a></h4>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Indassa kammam indriyam.<br>
(Indassa--of the rulers, governors, or controllers; kammam--act, i.e. act of
ruling, governing, or controlling; indriyam--hence called indriya). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>(The act of ruling by rulers. Hence
called indriya). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>'The act of ruling by rules' means,
wherever the ruler rules, nobody can go against him. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In this matter, the control or rule that
one exercises over one¡¦s mind is the essential factor. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>There are five indriya. They are: <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<ul type=disc>
 <ol start=1 type=1>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l0 level2 lfo10;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>saddhindriya <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l0 level2 lfo10;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>viriyindriya <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l0 level2 lfo10;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>satindriya <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l0 level2 lfo10;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>sam</span><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
      "Times New Roman"'>dhindriya <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l0 level2 lfo10;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>pa</span><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
      "Times New Roman"'>driya. <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 </ol>
</ul>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Saddhindriya is saddha (faith). There are
two kinds of saddha, namely: <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<ul type=disc>
 <ol start=6 type=1>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l0 level2 lfo10;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>pakati-saddha <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l0 level2 lfo10;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>bh</span><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
      "Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
      lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-saddha. <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 </ol>
</ul>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The saddha (faith and confidence) that
leads ordinary men and women to perform acts of d</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na
(alms-giving), s</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la (morality), and limitation
bh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
(mental concentration) is called pakati-saddha. Here, as was shown in the case
of the mad man, although saddha is said to be a controlling factor, the control
does not extend to the extent of controlling the unstable minds of ordinary
folk in the work of bh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.
Control is exercised over the instability only to the extent of leading to acts
of d</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The mind never leans towards kusala kamma
(wholesome volitional actions) without saddha, for ordinarily it takes delight
only in evil acts. This is true also in the case of effort to achieve s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la-visuddhi (purification of virtue), and
in the study of the sacred texts. This is how pakati kusala kamma are produced
by the control of pakati-saddha which has not been developed. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In the work of kammatthana (practice of
calm and insight), pakati- saddha has no control over the mind, for the mind is
apt to react and rebound from that saddha and proceed elsewhere. In kammatthana
work pakati-saddha is not sufficient. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-saddha prepares the seed-bed, so to say,
for the acquisition of great strength and power through the practice of bh</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
such as kammatthana exercises in out-breath and in-breath, etc. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In the matter of the
bodhipakkhiya-dhamma, it is this bh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-saddha that is called saddhindriya. In
the matter of kammatthana exercises, it represents the disappearance of
unstable and oscillating mental attention and the appearance of a clear and
steady mind. The mind¡¦s attention can be steadily fixed only on those objects
which it finds clear and unbefogged. The practice of k</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati,
such as anapana (in-breath and out-breath), is the preparation of the seed-bed
for bh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-saddha.
If the mind is fixed on k</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati, such as
out-breath and in-breath, it amounts to the attainment of bh</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-saddha.
If then the work be continued in the fields of samatha and vipassan</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, the ability to destroy the three planes
of sakk</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ya-di</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi
can be acquired even within this life. The work of samatha and vipassan</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> needs, for their proper performance, the
reliance on a teacher very learned in the Dhamma. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
