(craving), mana (conceit), and di</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi
(wrong view), and as such one must understand that saddha is prominent in that
s</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la. Inability to observe the requirements
of the s</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la is called 'breaking' it.
Although the s</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la may be technically
unbroken, if it is observed amidst ordinary worldly conditions, it is said to
be 'impure.' In accordance with the saying 'the worth of a bull can be known
only on the ascent from the bed of a stream to the banks', lay persons and
bhikkhus who profess to be followers of the Buddha can know whether or not the
turbulence and distractions latent in their minds have disappeared, i.e.
whether or not they have obtained mastery over their minds, only when they
arrive at these four constituents. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Kattha viriyindriya</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> datthabbada</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>?
Catusu sammappadh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>nesu ettha viriyindriya</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> datthabba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.[101]
(Where should one look for viriyindriya? One should look for it in the four
constituents of sammappadh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.)
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Lay persons and bhikkhus who profess to
be followers of the Buddha can know whether or not the dissettlement and
turbulence of their minds in the matter of v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya
have disappeared and whether or not they are thus persons who have obtained
mastery over their minds, only when they come to the four constituents of
sammappadh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>'Let my skin remain, let my sinews
remain, let my bones remain, let my blood dry up, I shall not rest until the
realm of sakk</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ya-di</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi,
the realm of the duccarita, and the apaya sa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra, that are in my personality, are
destroyed in this life.' This is the singleness of determination and effort in
sammappadh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.
It is the effort of the same order as the Venerable Cakkhupala¡¦s.[102] When one
encounters such determination and effort, one must recognise in it the
predominating control of v</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya over the mind. In the
matter of v</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya, the dissettlement and
turbulence of the mind have disappeared in such a person, and he is one within
the Buddha S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
who has obtained mastery over his mind. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Kattha satindriyam datthabbam? Catusu
satipatthanesa ettha satindriyam datthabbam.[103] (Where should one look for
satindriya? One should look for it in the four satipa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Lay persons and bhikkhus who profess to
be followers of the Buddha can know whether or not the dissettlement and
turbulence of their minds in the matter of sati (mindfulness) have disappeared,
and whether or not they are thus persons who have obtained mastery over their
minds, only when they arrive at the four constituents of the satipa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na.
If the attention can be kept fixed on any part of the body, such as out-breath
and in breath, by the successful practice of k</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati
for as long as is desired, then it must be recognised as the control exercised
by sati. The dissettlement and turbulence of the mind of such a person have
disappeared. He is one who has obtained mastery over his mind. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Kattha sam</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhindriyam
di</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>habba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>?
Catusu jh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>nesu ettha samm</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>- dhindriya</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
da</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>habba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.[104]
(Where should one look for sam</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhindriya? One should look for
it in the four jh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>If in the work of samatha, such as
out-breath and in-breath, the successful accomplishment in the least of upac</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra-sam</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi-bh</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
(contemplation of access-concentration) is attained, and if thereby the n</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>vara</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a
such as k</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>macchanda (sensuous desire),
byapada (ill-will), etc., which have continuously in the past sa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra
been running riot in the mind, are removed, the attention of the mind on the
objects of samatha becomes specially steady and tranquil. This must be
recognised as arising out of the function of the predominant control exercised
by sam</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi. The dissettlement and
disturbances of the mind in the matter of samadhi have disappeared from such an
individual. He is one who has obtained mastery over his mind. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Kattha pa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>bb</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>indriya</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> da</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>habba</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>? Catusu ariyasaccesu ettha pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bb</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>indriya</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
da</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>habba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.[105]
(Where should one look for pa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bb</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>indriya? One should look for
it in the Four Noble Truths). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Among persons who encounter a Buddha S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
knowledge of the Four Noble Truths is of supreme value. Only when this knowlege
is acquired can they obtain release from the realm of sakk</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ya-di</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi,
and that of the duccarita, and from the apaya sa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra. Hence, in order to acquire a
knowledge of the Four Noble Truths, they attempt in the least to obtain insight
into the six dhatu (or basic constituent elements) of pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>t</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hav</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
apo, tejo, vayo, akasa and vinnana,[106] or insight into their fleeting and
unstable nature--how they do not last for more than the twinkling of an eye at
a time (so to say) and how they are continually being destroyed--through such
methods of practice as studying, memorising, reciting, cogitating, listening,
discussing, questioning, practising insight exercises, and contemplating. If a
clear insight is obtained into these six elements, there is no necessity for
special practice with regard to the remaining dhamma.[107] If the nature of
anicca (impermanence) can be clearly realised the realisation of anatta
(impersonality) follows as a matter of course.[108] <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The realisation of the nature of dukkha
can be accomplished in its entirety only when one attains the stage of
arahatta-phala (fruition of holiness). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Thus, after putting forth effort for
lengthy periods, when insight is obtained into the nature of the six elements
both within and without oneself, as well as into the nature of their
impermanency, fixity of attention on them is achieved. This must be recognised
as arising out of the predominant control exercised by pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>. The unreliability that had been a
feature of one¡¦s mind throughout past infinite sa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra gradually disappears. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Here, 'unreliability of one¡¦s mind' means
the perception of permanency in things that are impermanent, of happiness in
suffering, of pleasantness in loathsomeness, of self in non-self, of
individuals in non-individuals, of beings in non-beings, of human in
non-humans, of devas, sakka and brahmas, of women, men, bullocks, buffaloes,
elephants, horses in non-men, non-bullocks, non-buffaloes, non-elephants, and
non-horses. Freedom from unreliability means perceiving the true reality after
having obtained mastery over the mind within the Buddha S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>If dukkha-sacca or the Noble Truth of
Suffering, be clearly perceived, it follows as a matter of course that the
other three sacca can also be clearly perceived. In the perception of these
Four Truths, the way that puthujjana perceive them is known as anubodha, while
the way of the ariyas is known as pativedha. Anubodha knowledge is like seeing
a light at night but not the fire. Although the fire cannot be directly seen,
by seeing the reflected light one can know without doubt that there is a fire.
Seeing the fire directly is like pativedha knowledge. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<pre style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Saddhinridya</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>veti,<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre
style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Viriyindriya</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>veti,<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre
style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Satindriya</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>veti,<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre
style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Sam</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhindriyam bh</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>veti,<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre
style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>bb</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>indriya</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>veti.[109]<o:p></o:p></span></pre>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The meaning of these P</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>al</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>i passages uttered by the Buddha is that
the five indriya (mental faculties) should be practised and developed in order
to facilitate the great work of samatha and vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The aggregate that we call the body
(khandha) of a person who has not developed these five indriya is like a
country without a ruler or king. It is like the forests and mountains inhabited
by wild tribes where no administration exists. In a rulerless or kingless
country there is no law. There, the people are unrestrained. Like animals, the
strong prey on the weak. In the same way, the mind of a person who has not
developed the five indriya is distracted, and runs riot with defilements. Just
as a person possessed by evil spirits cannot bear to hear the sound of such
verses as 'itipiso' or 'hetu paccayo', when persons without developed indriya
hear talks connected with the cause of contentment (paccaya santosa) or with
the practice of mental development (bh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>rambha), they quickly discover antithetic
criticisms. In them, the desire to exert themselves in the work of samatha and
vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> never arises. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>On the other hand, the khandha of a
person who develops the five indriya resembles a country ruled by a just and
lawful king. It resembles the towns and hamlets of the majjhima-desa
(mid-country) where governmental administration exists. Such a person is not
disturbed by the variegated theories of various persons. He is confirmed in the
sole way of the Buddha¡¦s teachings. When such a person hears talks connected
with the cause of contentment, or the practice of mental development, his mind
is clear and cool. He is confirmed in the desire to exert himself in the work
of samatha and vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In this way, the arising of two kinds of
desires in this world is not the work of beings or individuals, but depends on
the existence or otherwise of development of the five indriya. If there is no
development of the indriya, one kind of desire arises. If there is development
of the indriya, that desire disappears and a new kind of desire invariably
appears. The more the development of the indriya proceeds, the more does this
new desire increase and gather strength. When all the five indriya are set up,
the desire for the Paths and the Fruits will immediately appear. Thus must
beings develop the five indriya in order to raise pakati-saddha, v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya, sati, sam</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi
and pa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> (which are insignificant) to
great heights. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

