<h3 style='tab-stops:24.0pt'><a name="_Toc133723553"></a><a name="_Toc133724051"><span
style='mso-bookmark:_Toc133723553'><span lang=EN-US>VI, The Five Bala (or
Balani)</span></span></a></h3>

<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-left:36.0pt;text-align:center;
tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><img
width=466 height=3 id="_x0000_i2361"
src="6-THE%20MANUALS%20OF%20BUDDHISM,Bodhipakkhiya%20Dipani,VI.files\Bar.gif"><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Bala is defined: Patipakkha dhamme
baliyantiti balani.[110] (Suppresses opposition. Hence called bala.) The P</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>al</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>i Texts say: Akampanatthena balani.[111]
(Whenever opposition is encountered, there is fearless firmness. Hence called
bala.) <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>As in the case of the indriya, there are
five bala: <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<ul type=disc>
 <ol start=1 type=1>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l5 level2 lfo12;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>saddha <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l5 level2 lfo12;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>v</span><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
      "Times New Roman"'>riya <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l5 level2 lfo12;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>sati <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l5 level2 lfo12;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>sam</span><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
      "Times New Roman"'>dhi <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l5 level2 lfo12;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>pa</span><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
      "Times New Roman"'>. <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 </ol>
</ul>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>They are five generals or five commanders
for the purpose of destroying the kingdom of sakk</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ya-di</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi (personality-belief). They are the
five strengths that serve as reliance for bhikkhus and layfolk in the Buddha S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>As in the case of saddhindriya, saddha is
of two kinds: <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<ul type=disc>
 <ol start=6 type=1>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l5 level2 lfo12;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>pakati-saddha <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l5 level2 lfo12;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>bh</span><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
      "Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
      lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-saddha. <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 </ol>
</ul>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Pakati-saddha which has no development
through specific practice, associates with ta</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> according to circumstances, and can thus
produce only the pakati-kusala-kamma of d</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na,
s</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la, etc. It cannot overcome ta</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
with strength. On the other hand, ta</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>n</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> keeps pakati-saddha under its power. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>This is how ta</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> keeps pakati-saddha under its power. The
P</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>al</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>i Texts mention (as clearly as
exist the sun and moon in the heavens) four ariya-vamsa-dhamma.[112] They are: <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<ul type=disc>
 <ol start=8 type=1>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l5 level2 lfo12;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>being easily satisfied with food <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l5 level2 lfo12;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>being easily satisfied with
      clothing <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l5 level2 lfo12;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>being easily satisfied with
      dwelling place <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l5 level2 lfo12;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>finding pleasure and enjoyment in
      the work of bh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
      lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span
      lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>. <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 </ol>
</ul>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>They constitute the realm of saddha. In
the present-day world, this great kingdom of saddha lies hidden and submerged.
Today, beings take pleasure and enjoyment in material things (paccayamisa);
they take pleasure and enjoyment in worldly rank, dignity, and honour
(lokamisa); they take pleasure and enjoyment in the attainment of the pleasant
life, in worldly riches and in power and dominion (vattamisa); and thus is the
great kingdom of ta</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
established as clearly as the great ocean round the island. This shows the
weakness of pakati-saddha in this world. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>It is bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-saddha, which has its genesis in the
successful practice of k</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati, such as
out-breath and in-breath until the disappearance of the dissettlement and
distraction of the mind, that can dispel ta</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> which takes pleasure and enjoyment in
the three kinds of amisa. It is this bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-saddha that can save bhikkhus and
layfolk, who are in the course of being drowned and submerged in the ocean of
the three ta</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
and enable them to reach the island haven of the kingdom of saddha consisting
of the four ariyavamsa-dhamma. In the matter of the bodhi-pakkhiya-dhamma, it
is this saddha that should be acquired. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Of the two kinds of v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya, pakati- v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya
which has no development practice, associates with kosajja (laziness) according
to occasion and produces the pakati-kusala-kamma of d</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na,
the study of the sacred texts, etc. This pakati- v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya
cannot dispel kosajja subdues pakati-v</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>When beings encounter a Buddha S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
they acquire the knowledge that in the past infinite sa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra they have been the kinsfolk of sakk</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ya-di</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi,
the duccarita, and the apaya loka. The sacred P</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>al</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>i
Texts clearly prescribe the method of the ariyavamsa, which consists of
dispelling kosajja (laziness) and devoting the whole time to bh</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>rama
(delight in meditation) till release from such state is attained. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>...The act of dispelling kosajja may be
thus described. Having equipped oneself with the sikkha (trainings--which are
the Buddha¡¦s heritage) and which one undertook in the sima (ordination hall) at
the time of becoming a bhikkhu, sikkha auch as the undertaking <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<pre style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>rukkhamula senasanam nissaya pabbajja, tattha teyava jivam<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre
style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>ussaho karaniyo.[113]<o:p></o:p></span></pre>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>and in accordance with such sikkha, if
one makes trees and bushes in the forests as one¡¦s dwelling place, lives only
on alms-round, does not associate with other persons, observes the dhuta</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga (ascetic practice) steadfastly, and
practises k</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati scrupulously,
these are acts of v</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya that dispel the akusala
kamma (unwholesome volitional actions) arising out of kosajja. They are acts
comprised within the realm of v</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>This realm of v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya
remains obscure and is unknown in the present-day world. Today, although
bhikkhus are aware that they belong to that class of beings possessed of sakk</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ya-di</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi,
the duccarita, and the liability to rebirth in the apaya loka, they live
permanently in dwelling places constructed within towns and villages by dayakas
(or donors), they take pleasure and enjoyment in the receipt of large gifts and
benefits, they are unable to discard the society of other people, etc. all of
which acts are comprised within the realm of kosajja and this realm of kosajja
is as conspicuous as the sea which has inundated an island. This shows the
weakness of pakati-v</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>It is only bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya,
such as being satisfied with the minimum of sleep, being always alert and
active, being fearless, being bold and firm in living alone, being steadfast in
mental advertence, that can dispel kosajja. In the matter of the
bodhipakkhiya-dhamma, it is this bh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya
that should be acquired. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The detailed meaning of the bala of sati,
sam</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi, and pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> may be known by following the lines of
explanation outlined above. Here, I shall give just a concise explanation. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The antithesis of sati is the akusala
kamma called mutthasacca. Mutthasacca means inability to become absorbed in the
work of samatha- bh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>--such
as in k</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati--or in the work of
vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> - bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> inability to concentrate, inability to
control one¡¦s mind, and the wandering of thoughts to objects other than the
object concentrated on. The pakati-sati that one possesses in its natal state
from birth cannot dispel mutthasacca. It is only bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-sati that can dispel it. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The antithesis of sam</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi is the akusala kamma of vikkhepa[114]
(restlessness of mind). It consists of the inability to concentrate, and of
unquietness and restlessness of mind in the work of bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> manasik</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra.
It is the arising of thoughts on objects other than the object of
concentration. It is the inability to control the mind and keep its attention
fixed on one object. Pakati-sam</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi cannot dispel that akusala
kamma of vikkhepa. Only bh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-sam</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi can dispel it. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The antithesis of pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> is the akusala kamma of sammoha.[115] It
consists of ignorance, lack of clarity, mistiness, and absence of light of the
mind. It is the darkness that surrounds the mind. This sammoha cannot be
dispelled by pakati-pa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, nor by pariyatti-pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> which may comprise a knowledge of the
whole of the Ti-Pi</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>t</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>aka. It is only bh</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> that has set up k</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati which can gradually dispel
sammoha. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>This shows the meaning of the five
patipakkha akusala dhamma coupled with their respective bala. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The five patipakkha akusala dhamma are:
1) ta</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
2) kosajja, or laziness, or inability to take pains, or lack of fearlessness in
the work of the patipatti, 3) mutthasacca, 4) vikkhepa, and 5) sammoha. The
five dhamma that can counteract and dispel these akusala dhamma are called
bala. If any one of these five bala is weak and unable to dispel the respective
patipakkha dhamma,[116] work in samatha and vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp; </span>cannot be very successful as far as
neyya individuals are concerned. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Hence, at the present day, some persons
can emerge out of the realm of ta</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>n</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> because of their strength in
saddha-bala. They are rid of the attachments to paccaya amisa and worldly
dignities and honours. But since they are deficient in the other four bala,
they are unable to rise above the stage of santutthi (state of being
contented). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Some persons can emerge out of the realm
of ta</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
and kosajja because they are strong in saddha-bala and v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya-bala. They are constant in the
observance of the santosa dhamma[117] in residence among hills and forests, and
in the practice of the dhuta</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga (ascetic practices). But
because they are weak in the other three bala, they are unable to practise k</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati, or do the work of samatha
and vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Some persons are strong in the first
three bala and thus can rise up to the work of k</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati.
They achieve concentration in out-breath, or in the bones of the body. But
since they are deficient in the other two bala, they cannot rise up to the work
of the jh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na and vipassan</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Some persons can rise up to the
attainment of jh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na samapatti because they are
strong in the first four bala, but since they are weak in pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-bala, they cannot rise up to the work of
vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Some persons are strong in pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-bala. They are learned in the Dhamma and
the Pi</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>t</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>akas. They are wise in the
paramattha dhamma (ultimate realities). But because the back is broken in the
four other bala, they cannot emerge from the realm of ta</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
kosajja, mutthasacca and vikkhepa. They live and die within the confines of
these akusala. In this way, whenever one is deficient in any one of the bala,
one cannot emerge out of the realm of the respective patipakkha. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Of the five bala, v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya-bala and pa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
"Times New Roman"'>-bala are also iddhipada. Hence, if these two bala are
strong and co-ordinated, it does not happen that one cannot rise up to the work
of vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> because of the weakness of
the other three bala. As an illustration, consider the case of the five crores
and five lakhs of householders in Savatthi City during the Buddha¡¦s time who
obtained release from ills. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>People who do not know the functions of
the iddhipada, the indriya, and the bala, do not know why their desires are
weak, and what patipakkha assails them. They do not know what dhamma they have
to set up, and the desire to set them up never arises. It is thus that the
ariyavamsa-dhamma are on the verge of disappearance at the present day. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>I shall give an illustration. There is a
species of bull called usabha. It is a bull worth more than a thousand or ten
thousand ordinary bulls. If the characteristics and distinctive signs of that
bull be recognised, and it be reared and nurtured properly, its limbs and marks
will develop, and its strength and powers will increase. It can then guard even
a hundred cattle pens from the incursions of lions and leopards. The cattle in
the enclosures where such a bull exists will be free from major diseases and epidemics.
People living in houses round the stockade, up to the seventh house in each
direction, will be free from major diseases and epidemics. Like the bull Nandi
Visala,[118] it can draw even five hundred carts at a time. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>If the owner of such a bull is ignorant
of all these, and if thus he does not rear and nurture it properly but keeps
and tends it just as he would any other ordinary bull, if he employs it in
ploughing and drawing carts in company with other bulls, its distinctive marks
and limbs will fail to develop, and its strength and powers will remain
dormant. It will thus live and die just like any other bull. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>A knowing owner, however, will separate
such a bull from the rest and keep it in a specially constructed shed. He will
cover the floor of the shed with clean sand and will fix a ceiling to the roof.
He will keep the shed clean of urine and excreta, and will feed the bull with
paddy and pulses fit for human consumption. He will wash and bathe it, and
apply cosmetics and unguents. In such a case, the distinctive marks and limbs
will develop, and its strength and powers will increase enormously. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In this Buddha S</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, neyya individuals resemble the owner of
the bull. The five bala of these neyya individuals resemble the usabha bull.
The satipa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na
vibha</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga, sammappadh</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
vibha</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga, iddhipada vibha</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga, indriya vibha</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga,
bojjha</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga vibha</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga, and magga</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga
vibha</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga, of the Abhidhamma Pi</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>t</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>aka and the Mah</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>satipa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na
Sutta, satipa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na
sa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yutta, sammappadh</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
sa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yutta, iddhipada sa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yutta, indriya sa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yutta,
bala sa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yutta, and bojjha</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga sa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yutta
of the Sutta Pi</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>t</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>aka, resemble the worldly
expository books which expound the distinctive signs, marks, and
characteristics, of usabha bulls, the methods how such bulls are to be reared
and taken care of, and the strength and powers that such bulls can attain if
reared and nurtured properly. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Those neyya individuals who through
ignorance do not attempt to develop the five bala through the work of bh</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
and who thus remain satisfied with the lower attainments within the S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
such as d</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na, s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la,
and the study of pariyatti-dhamma, resemble the ignorant owner of an usabha
bull who does not rear and nurture it properly. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In this world, there are many kinds of
worldly undertakings. There are undertakings that can be accomplished by the
strength of wealth, and there are undertakings that can be accomplished by the
strength of knowledge. Even in the case of the cultivation of land, several
kinds of strength are needed for its accomplishment. Sometimes the strength of wealth
has to be garnered first, and at other times the strength of knowledge.
Preparatory education and study constitute the garnering of the strength of
knowledge. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Similarly, in the Buddha S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
there are five bala needed for the work of samatha, vipassan</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, and the attainment of the holy Paths
and Fruits and Nibb</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na. It is only when these bala
are first accumulated that the great worlks mentioned can be undertaken. Those
persons who do not possess even one of the five bala cannot evoke a desire to
undertake these great tasks. It does not occur to them that those great tasks
can be accomplished in this life. They live forgetfully and without
determination. If it is pointed out to them that the tasks can be accomplished,
they do not wish to hear it. They do not know that such untoward thoughts occur
to them because they are utterly impoverished in the bala. They lay the blame
at the door of p</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ram</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
or dvi-hetuka, or at the times.[119] <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>If, however, these people set up work in
one of the satipa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na,
such as in anapana-sati, and if thereby they set up the three bala of saddha, v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya, and sati, such untoward thoughts
will certainly disappear. It is inevitable that new wholesome thoughts must
arise. This is because they have developed their strength. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>This is how the strength is developed.
Although such a person cannot as yet attain an insight into r</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>u</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>pa and n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ma,
the weak saddha develops through the control exercised on paccayamisa- ta</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
and lokamisa-tanh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>. The weak v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya develops through the control of kosajja.
The weak sati develops through the control of mutthasacca. Sam</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi and pa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
"Times New Roman"'> also gather strength through the control of vikkhepa and
sammoha. When these bala develop, it is inevitable that there must be a change
in his mind. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>A person who is afflicted with a major
disease, such as leprosy, has no desire to take an interest in the ordinary
affairs and undertakings of the world. But if after taking the proper medicines
and treatment, the great sickness is gradually cured and he is aroused from his
apathy. This is inevitable. The group of five akusala kamma of ta</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
kosajja mutthasacca, vikkhepa, and sammoha, resemble five major
sicknesses.[120] In the S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
the work of samatha and vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-bh</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>van</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
resembles the affairs and undertakings of the world. The work of satipa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na,
