lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre
style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>--Verse 374.<o:p></o:p></span></pre>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>[The Bhikkhu who retires to a
lonely abode and has a calm mind, experiences joy transcending that of men, as
he clearly perceives the dhamma. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The formation and disintegration of
whichever part of the body the yogi contemplates, he experiences joy and
happiness as he can thereby perceive the Deathless state (Nibb</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na).] <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>If the pleasure and joy experienced in
vipassan</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-sukha, which is complete with
the seven characteristics of sambodhi, be divided into 256 parts, one part of
that joy and pleasure exceeds the worldly joys and plesures of kings among
humans, devas, and Brahmas--so great is the joy and pleasure inherent in the sambodhi.
Hence also did the Buddha say: <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>¡¥Sabba rasam dhammaraso jinati[125]¡¦ (The
flavour of the dhamma exceeds all other flavours.) <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>There are stories wherein it is related
that major diseases and ailments have been cured by the mere hearing[126] of
the recitation of these seven characteristics of sambodhi. But, these diseases
and ailments can be cured only when the hearers are fully aware of their
meaning, and great and clear saddha (faith) arises. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>When these seven characteristics or
sambodhi are acquired in a balanced manner, the yogavac</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra
can rest assured that there is no deficiency in his k</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati.
He can rest assured that there is no deficiency in his perception of anicca or
anatta, and in his mental and bodily energy. Because his mind is set at rest in
regard to these three factors, he experiences joy in the knowledge that he can
now perceive the light of Nibb</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na which has never before
appeared to him in the past infinite sa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra, even in his dreams. Because of that
joy and ease of mind, his attention on the kammatthana objects becomes
extremely calm and steady and upekkha (equanimity) which is free from the
anxieties and efforts for mindfulness, perception of anicca and anatta, and the
necessity to evoke energy, arises. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>All the above statements are made with
reference to the stage at which the sambojjha</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga
are in unison with one another and their respective functions are specially
clear. As far as ordinary sambojjhahga are concerned, from the moment k</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati is set up, the dhamma such as
sati are known as sambojjha</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>When the Buddha said that the seven
sambojjanga must be practised, as in: Satisambojjha</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>veti,
viveka nissita</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, viraga nissita</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, nirodha nissita</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
vossaggaparinami</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>... upekkha sambojjha</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
bh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>veti, viveka nissita</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, viraga nissitam, nirodha nissitam,
vossaggaparinamim', [127] it is meant that in the ordinary course, the process
of setting up k</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>yagata-sati (such as
out-breath and in-breath) amounts to the setting up of the seven bojjha</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga. For the distinctive and specific
setting up of the bojjha</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga, see the Commentary on the
Bojjha</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga Vibha</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga.[128] <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The meaning of the P</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>al</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>i passage above is: 'One should practise
sati-sambojjha</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga which is dependent on the
absence of all kinds of activities and anxieties, of lust and greed, or
suffering attendant on the round of rebirths, and on the abandonment of the
four substratu</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> of upadhi.[129] <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Viveka nisita, viraga nissita, nirodha
nissita, mean 'having no leanings towards bhava-sampatti[130] and
bhoga-sampatti,[131] attempting to destroy the great realm of latent sakk</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ya-di</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi
in this very 1ife, and thus is free from dependence on the round of rebirths.'
Vivatta nissita means freeing oneself day by day from the attachments of
sensuous passions, the meanings of bojjha</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga,
sambojja</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga, and sambodhi a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga are identical. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

