<h3 style='tab-stops:24.0pt'><a name="_Toc133723569"></a><a name="_Toc133724055"><span
style='mso-bookmark:_Toc133723569'><span lang=EN-US>X Heritage of the </span></span></a><span
lang=EN-US>S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US>san</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span></h3>

<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-left:36.0pt;text-align:center;
tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><img
width=466 height=3 id="_x0000_i2375"
src="10-THE%20MANUALS%20OF%20BUDDHISM,Bodhipakkhiya%20Dipani,X.files\Bar.gif"><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>I shall now examine what constitutes S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dayajja.
S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dayajja
means the act of receiving the heritage of S</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>'Databbanti dayam'. (That which is given
as heritage is called daya). Property that should be given as heritage by
parents to their children. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>'Dayam adadatiti dayado.' (Fit to receive
heritage. hence called dayado.) Children or heirs who are fit to receive heritage.
'Dayadassa kammam dayajjam.' (The act of receiving the heritage by heirs. Hence
called dayajjam. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>' S</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ssa dayajja</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
sasanadayajja</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.' (The act of receiving the
heritage of the Sasana. Hence called sasanadayajja</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.)
It is also called Buddhadayajja (the act of receiving the heritage of the
Buddha.) <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>First, I shall show the nature of the
heritage. In the S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
there are two kinds of heritages, namely amisa and Dhamma. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The four requisites of a bhikkhu, namely,
alms-food, robes, dwelling place, and medicines, are called amisa heritage. The
three sikkha of s</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la, sam</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi and pa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
"Times New Roman"'>, the seven visuddhi, such as s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la-visuddhi,
citta visuddhi, etc., the thirty-seven bodhipakkhiya-dhamma, such as the four
satipa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na,
the four sammappadh</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
etc., are called the Dbamma heritage. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>'There are two kinds of Dhamma heritage,
namely: <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<ul type=disc>
 <ol start=1 type=1>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l9 level2 lfo18;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>lokiya dhamma heritage <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l9 level2 lfo18;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>lokuttara dhamma heritage. <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 </ol>
</ul>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The lokiya-sikkha of s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la, sam</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi,
and pa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, the six lokiya-visuddhi, and
the thirty-seven bodhipakkhiya-dhamma associated with the lokiya-visuddhi, are
called the lokiya dhamma heritage. The sikkha associated with the holy Paths
and the Fruits, the lokuttara-</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>ban</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>adassana-visuddhi, and the
thirty-seven bodhipakkhiya-dhamma are called lokuttara dhamma heritage. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Lokiya dhamma heritage may be divided
into: <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<ul type=disc>
 <ol start=3 type=1>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l9 level2 lfo18;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>vatta nissita dhamma heritage <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l9 level2 lfo18;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>vivatta nissita dhamma heritage. <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 </ol>
</ul>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>or into: <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<ul type=disc>
 <ol start=5 type=1>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l9 level2 lfo18;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>niyata dhamma heritage <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l9 level2 lfo18;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>aniyata dhamma heritage, <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 </ol>
</ul>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The practice of s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la,
sam</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi, and pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> directed towards the attainment of
worldly positions such as mentor and teacher of kings, or towards the
acquisition of power, retinue, and property, or towards the the attainment in
sa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra
of rebirth as noble and highly placed humans and devas, is called vatta nissita
dhamma heritage. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>There are three forms of rounds of
rebirths (vatta), namely, kilesa-vatta, kamma-vatta and vipaka-vatta.[149]
Vivatta means Nibb</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na which is the end of these
rounds of rebirth. The practice of s</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la,
sam</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi, and pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> directed towards the ending of the three
forms of rounds of rebirths is called vivatta nissita dhamma heritage. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The practice of kusala kamma directed
towards the ultimate attainment of Nibb</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na,
as of worldly benefits and pleasant rebirths in the interim before Nibb</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na is attained, is related to both vatta
and vivatta, and hence is called ubhava-nissita. In the P</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>al</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>i texts, however, only vatta and vivatta
are mentioned. Those who are more inclined to the attainment of vatta results
may be said to perform vatta nissita kamma, and those who are more inclined to
the attainment of vivatta results may be said to perform vivatta nissita kusala
kamma. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>With reference to the classification of
niyata and aniyata, the great realm of sakk</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ya-di</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi anusaya that puthujjana (worldlings)
possess is like a great, wide and deep ocean of hot burning embers. The s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la, sam</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi
and pa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> that occasionally occur to
puthujjana may be compared to droplets of rain falling on that great ocean of
burning embers. 'I fulfill s</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la. I possess s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la. I develop samadhi. I am knowing. I am
wise. I am clever. I perceive r</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>u</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>pa and n</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ma. I contemplate r</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>u</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>pa and n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ma¡¦
are declarations of acts of s</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la, sam</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi, and pa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
"Times New Roman"'>,which revolve round the sakk</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ya-di</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi that is ¡¥I¡¦, and thus resemble the
droplets of rain falling on the great ocean of burning embers. Just as the
great ocean of burning embers scorch and dry-up the droplets of rain and cause
their disappearance, so does the great kingdom of sakk</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ya-di</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi cause the disappearance of such s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la, sam</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi,
and pa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>. Hence, the s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la, sam</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi,
and pa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, appearing in puthujjana are
of the aniyata class. Although puthujjana may possess s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la,
sam</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi, and pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> the possession is tada</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ga or temporary. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The </span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>j</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>va</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hamaka
lokiya s</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la of sotapanna, their lokiya
sam</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi which resides steadily on
the noble and incomparable qualities of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>gha, and their lokiya pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> which perceives the Four Noble Truths
are of the niyata class, Like droplets of water falling on the great lake of
Anavatatta, such lokiya s</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la, sam</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi, and pa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
"Times New Roman"'> do not disappear throughout many lives and many
world-cycles. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>This shows the nature of lokiya dhamma
heritage. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The lokuttara Dhamma of s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la, sam</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi,
kind pa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, </span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>ban</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
"Times New Roman"'>adassana-visuddhi, and the thirty-seven
bodhipakkhiya-dhamma, which accompany the eight kinds of lokuttara
consciousness are vivatta nissita. They are niyata. The lokiya s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la, sam</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi,
and pa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, which occur to ariya who
have attained lokuttara s</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la, sam</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>dhi, and pa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
"Times New Roman"'>, also reach the niyata stage. In such persons there is no
longer any possibility of their becoming duss</span><span lang=EN-US
