lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ni kamm</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ni nayanti duggati</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre
style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp; </span><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>--Dhammapada, verse 240.<o:p></o:p></span></pre>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>(Just as rust springs from iron and eats
away that self-same iron, the deeds arising out of amisa ta</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>h</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
of a person who lives without reflection lead him to the </span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>paya loka.) <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>This discourse[156] was delivered by the
Buddha in connection with a bhikkhu who died in the Jetavana Monastery, and who
was reborn as a louse in his erstwhile bhikhhu¡¦s robes, because he harboured an
attachment to those robes just before he died. lf the attachment to a set of
robes can cast one in the apaya loka, what more need be said on greater
attachments? <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The robes were received as a share from
sanghika property (property belonging to the order of the Sa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>gha), and hence were dhammika property
(righteous or lawful property). The bhikkhu in question was also one who
scrupulously observed the 227 sikkha of the Vinaya. Thus it may be said that a
set of lawful robes cast a bhikkhu endowed with the 227 sikkha into the apaya
loka. What more need be said about properties acquired with lust and greed by
ordinary layfolk endowed with only five sikkha? It is thus that one should
contemplate and acquire agitation (sa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>vega).[157]
I shall now give an illustration. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>There was a wealthy man who possessed
many crores worth of silver, many crores worth of gold, and many crores worth
of pearls. In order that these properties might not be lost during bad times,
he buried the bulk of them in the ground, and kept only sixty-thousand worth of
money, rice, paddy, wearing apparel, and ornaments for immediate and ready use.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>This wealthy man had six sons. On his
death, the six heirs divided the properties among themselves in six equal
shares. The properties buried beneath the earth were also similarly allocated.
These buried properties could be secured by the heirs only if the owners
personally dug them out the ground. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>One of the sons was full of greed. he was
not content with the property he could immediately use. He was satiated with
the desire for the buried property and could not bear to wait long in order to
get it. He therefore exerted himself and dug up the property, thus becoming a
wealthy man. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>One of the sons was full of energy. He
did not look on the prospect of having to exert himself for days and months as
burdensome. He therefore put forth effort and applied himself to the work of
unearthing the buried treasure, thus becoming a wealthy man. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>One of the sons was strong in his
attachment. From the moment he received the heritage, his mind ways always on
the property. Sleep and food were of no consequence, so greatly was his mind
attached to the property. He thus put forth effort and dug up the buried
property, becoming a wealthy man. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>One of the sons was clever and ingenious.
He contrived to construct machinery and dug up the buried property, thus
becoming a wealthy man. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>One of the sons lacked greed. He imagined
himself to be well-off with even ten thousand worth of property. He had no
desire to acquire the buried property. He was satisfied with the property that
he received for his imediate use. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>One of the sons was a spendthrift. He
squandered all the property, not even leaving the price of a spade for the
exhumation of the buried property. He sank into bad ways and was eventually
banished from his native place. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In this illustration, the Buddha
resembles the wealthy father. S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la-visuddhi and the pariyatti
dhamma resemble the treasure available for immediate use. Jh</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>na and abhhinna, which constitute
citta-visuddhi, resemble the buried silver treasure. The four lokiya pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>-visuddhi, such as di</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hi-visuddhi, resemble the buried gold
treasure. The lokuttara-</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>ban</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a-dassana-visuddhi resembles
the buried pearl treasure. The layfolk and bhikkhus of the Buddha S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
resemble the six heirs. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Those persons within the S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
who are filled with the iddhipada of chanda (desire) resemble the first son who
was filled with greed. Persons filled with the iddipada of chanda are not
satisfied with the mere acquisition of s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la-visuddhi
and the pariyatti dhamma. They do not think that by such acquisition they have
encountered the Buddha S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
or that they have become heirs of the S</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>. They nurture great desire for attaining
the higher visuddhi and will not rest until they are achieved. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Those persons who possess the iddhipada
of v</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya (effort) resemble the second
son who was full of effort. Such persons are happy and easy in mind only when
they are engaged in the attempt to acquire the higher achievements which they
do not as yet possess. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Those persons who possess the iddhipada
of citta (attachment) resemble the third son who possessed strong attachment.
Whenever such persons come to know of work productive of great benefits, they
invoke great attachment for it, and their minds do not wander to any other
matter. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Those persons who possess iddhipada of pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> (wisdom) resemble the fourth son who was
clever and ingenious. Such persons attain happiness and ease of mind only when
they are engaged in the attempt to acquire great knowledge that is difficult of
acquisition, deep, and productive of great benefits. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Those persons who do not possess any of
the iddhipada, who possess only inferior chanda, v</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya,
citta, and pa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>bba</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, resemble the fifth son who
was easily satisfied with the unburied property. Such persons who lack saddha
and chanda do not even possess the idea that the higher attainments of the
visuddhi are the heritages which they can acquire in this very life. Because
they lack v</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>riya, they are reluctant to
put forth effort that requires the encountering of privations. They are liable
to reject such effort as impossible. Because they are weak in their volitions,
their minds are not fixed on such kinds of work. They change their minds
whenever they listen to various theories and lack knowledge and wisdom, they
reject such work as beyond their capabilities. It is because the Buddha had
such persons in view that he said: <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<pre style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Chandiddhipada</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>veti<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre
style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Viriyidipada</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>veti<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre
style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Cittiddhipada</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> bh</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>veti<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre
style='margin-left:36.0pt'><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'><span style="mso-spacerun: yes">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>V</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ma</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>siddhipada bh</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>veti.<o:p></o:p></span></pre>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In these words the Buddha urged all
beings to strengthen their weak iddhipada, such as chanda, etc. Then only can
new desires and new thoughts arise. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In the Buddha S</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>, layfolk and bhikkhus who are defective
in their moral conduct resemble the sixth son. Among layfolk, those persons who
are defective in the establishment of the Ti-sara</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>n</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a,
and the nicca-s</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la of pa</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>b</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ca-s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la
and </span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>j</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>va</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hamaka-s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la,
do not possess the qualities of an upasaka or an upasika, who only are the
heirs of the S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.
Among bhikkhus and samaneras, those who commit the parajika[158] offences do
not possess the qualities of a good bhikkhu or a good samanera, who only are
the heirs of the S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.
If layfolk vow that they would keep the pa</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>b</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ca-s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la or the </span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>j</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>va</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>tt</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>hamaka-s</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>i</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>la from today, they can immediately
become upasakas and upasikas who are heirs of the S</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>This illustration shows how of the many
persons who are truly in the line of heritage of the one father (the Buddha),
only those who possess one or other of the four iddhipada as a foundation can
enjoy the full benefits of the heritages. Persons who do not possess one or
other of the four iddhipada get the opportunity to enjoy only some of the
superficial benefits of the heritages. They do not get the opportunity to enjoy
the real essence of the heritages. Some persons do not get the opportunity of
enjoying even the superficial benefits because they squander their heritages
and thus become severed from the Buddha¡¦s and the S</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a¡¦</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s heritages. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The heirs of the S</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
may also be classified into: <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<ul type=disc>
 <ol start=16 type=1>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l9 level2 lfo18;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>niyata heirs <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:
      auto;mso-list:l9 level2 lfo18;tab-stops:list 72.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
      style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>aniyata heirs <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 </ol>
</ul>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>People who have never once obtained
anicca-</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>ban</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a and anatta-</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>ban</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>a within themselves are called aniyata
heirs. Aniyata means that they may be the disciples of the sabbannuta Buddha
(Omniscient Buddha)--or the heirs of the sabbannuta Buddha--today, but they may
become the disciples and heirs of another teacher tomorrow. They may even scorn
and destroy the S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
of the sabannuta Buddha. Even in the present world there are persons who have
changed their faith from the Buddha S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:
Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> to Christianity, and who scorn and
undermine the Buddha S</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>san</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.
How easily they can change after death in another birth can be imagined. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>One can be a disciple of the sabbannuta
Buddha this month, and the disciple of another, teacher next month. One can be
the disciple of the sabbannuta Buddha this year, and the disciple of another
teacher the next. One can be the disciple of the sabbannuta Buddha in the first
period of life and the disciple of another teacher in the second. One can be
the disciple of the sabbannuta Buddha in the second period of life and the
disciple of another in the third. One can be the disciple of the sabbannuta
Buddha in this life and the disciple and the disciple of another teacher in the
next. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Thus in the Patisambhidha-Magga, the
Buddha said: Nanasattarana</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'> mukha</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
ullokentiti puthujjana.[159] (A puthujjana is so called because he looks up to
the faces of various teachers). <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The meaning of this passage is that in
the infinite past sa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra,
puthujjana have never been constant in the choice of the teachers in whom they
have taken refuge. It has been one teacher today and another tomorrow. One
teacher this month and another the next. One teacher this year and another the
next. One teacher this life and another the next. The number of occasions on
which they have approached and taken refuge in the Sabbannuta Buddha during the
infinite past sa</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:Foreign1'>m</span><span
lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>s</span><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:Foreign1'>a</span><span lang=EN-US style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ra
is very few indeed. Sometimes, they have taken refuge in the Brahma, sometimes
in the Sakka, sometimes in the various devas, sometimes in the sun, sometimes
in the moon sometimes in the planets, sometimes in the spirits of the earth,
and sometimes in the ogres, and they have done so as if these refuges were
almighty. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p style='margin-left:36.0pt;tab-stops:24.0pt'><span lang=EN-US
style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In the world, the number of false
teachers is very numerous. The number of existences in which puthujjana have
approached and taken refuge in these false teachers is also very numerous.
Sometimes they have taken refuge in the nagas, sometimes in garudas, sometimes
in rivers, sometimes in mountains, sometimes in forests, sometimes in trees,
